  <div class="grid__item three-fifths lap-two-thirds palm-one-whole">
    <p class="lead">For the database to be fully searchable, we all need to record the census information in the same way. This page has the details of what to put where in your transcription. It also includes some general principles and information on the abbreviations that we need to use.</p>

    <h2 id="guidance">The guiding principles of transcribing</h2>
    <h3>Work as quickly as possible</h3>
    <p>Without sacrificing typing accuracy, get each transcription done as quickly as possible, recording difficult to read entries as your best guess. Behind you will be a Proofreader who will go through your transcription record by record and attempt to resolve any problems. Behind them is a Validator. So two more, experienced people will get to look at those difficult to read entries.</p>
    <p>Having said that, it is also important to pace yourself: pause before you actually feel tired; get up from your computer and do something else for a while.</p>
    
    <h3>The <q>as is</q> rule</h3>
    <p>The general rule is to transcribe <q>as is</q>, including spelling mistakes and other errors by the enumerator. The task is to take the information that is hand written on the census page and set it out so that it can be stored and searched in a database. The researcher will then interpret the data, not us. However tempting it may be to <q>correct</q> what the enumerator has written, it is dangerous to presume that we can know for certain what the entry should have been.</p>
    <p>There are a few specific exceptions to this rule which will be described below. These are mainly to do with standardising the way the data is recorded.</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">The main exceptions to the <q>as is</q> rule are:</p>
    <ul class="needsSpace">
      <li><strong>Expand all dittos:</strong> Enumerators often used <q>ditto</q>, or <q>do</q> or <q> <sub style="font-size: 1em;">''</sub> </q> to indicate that an entry such as surname should be the same as the one above. While this works on the written page, it does not work in a database where the record for every individual has to stand alone. So always type the entry in full.</li>
      <li><strong>Abbreviate where necessary:</strong> Because there are limits to the length of each field in the database, abbreviations may be necessary. See the lists of standard abbreviations in the Appendices, including the <a href="/information-for-transcribers/abbreviations#abbrev">Abbreviations policy</a> for details.</li>
      <li><strong>Expand known abbreviations</strong>, for example for <a href="/information-for-transcribers/abbreviations#occupation">common occupations</a>: Enumerators were instructed to abbreviate common occupations for the 1841 census. Thus “FS” was used for “Female Servant”, “J” for “Journeyman” and so on. Some enumerators continued to use these on later census returns. Where these are recognised abbreviations, they should be entered in full.</li>
      <li><strong>Do not use a <q>?</q>
</strong> in any field other than Y, Notes. In other words, do not use a question mark for something that you cannot read or where a place of birth or a surname, for example, is recorded as “unknown” or “NK” or anything similar. The only exception to this is that the Notes field can contain a <q>?</q> to indicate a doubt about an entry.</li>
      <li><strong>Do not enter any special characters</strong>, such as fractions, accented letters or similar. These could disrupt the search and lead to a record not being found by Researchers.</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Use lower case</h3>
    <p>We suggest that you type your entries in lower-case letters, to save keystrokes and so time: the appropriate capital (upper-case) letters will be put in automatically before your file becomes part of the database. The only exception is the <em>Notes field</em> (column Y): if your note is intended for the database, please type capital letters where appropriate.</p>
    <h3>Duplicate and blank pages</h3>
    <p>If you are sure that you have received two copies of the same page, then only transcribe the first. Similarly, if an enumerator has left a page blank, do not record anything.</p>
    <h3>Entering a hyphen</h3>
    <p>If you find that entering (only) a hyphen in a cell does not work as expected, enter instead as <strong>'-</strong> (single-quote hyphen).</p>
    <h3>Save regularly</h3>
    <p>We recommend that you save your spreadsheet regularly: at the end of each page is a good habit. If you work down the columns (rather than across the rows), take the opportunity to check that the column entries are complete down to the last person on a page.</p>
    <h3>Learn the lingo</h3>
    <p>Spreadsheets have rows and columns: these are temporary and are transformed, in the database, to records and fields respectively. We sometimes use the sets of terms interchangeably: fields and columns are essentially the same, as are records and rows.</p>
