    <div id="address">
      <h3>Schedule &amp; Address Details</h3>

      <h4>Field E: Schedule Number</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and can be up to 3 numerals plus an optional suffix, <strong>###a</strong> </li>
        <li>The default entry is “0” (zero)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>This is the first column on most census pages.  Schedule Numbers were used to identify the start of each separate household.  Enter the schedule number on the first line of each new household.  A suffix should be entered where it is present on the Census page, exactly as it is on the page.</p>
      <p>In the FreeCEN process, column E provides the ‘trigger’ to recognise each separate household or building.  A value <em>must</em> be entered in Column E for every new household, and “0” (zero) should be entered where, for whatever reason, the enumerator failed to enter a schedule number for a new household.  For instance, where the Enumerator has entered two separate families, each with its own Head, under a single schedule number, a zero should be entered on the first line of the second family.</p>
      <p>Please note that Schedule numbers were not used in the <strong>1841</strong> census, and “0” (zero) should be entered on the first line of each household.</p>
      <p>All Schedule Numbers must be accounted for: where the enumerator has, for whatever reason, omitted a schedule number, enter that number in Column E, and put <strong>n</strong> in Column H.</p>
      <p>Enter zero in Column E against each house recorded by the enumerator as uninhabited or being built.  Sometimes the enumerator entered the number of such buildings on the same line as the next household.  These must be entered separately in the transcription, with one line for each such building. For further guidance on how to transcribe such entries, please refer to <a href="#H">column H</a> below.</p>
      <p>If an enumeration contains more than 999 numbered schedules, then enter the sequence of schedule numbers as “999”, “000!”, “001!”, “002!”, etc. (When the file is uploaded to the database, a bit of software magic will convert such entries to the appropriate schedule numbers).  If any suffix is attached to such a schedule number, this should be explained as a note in column Y. Don't enter (for example) “002!a”.</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Institutions and Shipping Returns:</h5>
      <p>Schedule numbers were not used in these returns. Treat an Institution as a single household (even if a very large one) that may contain several individuals identified as “Head”, “Wife”, etc. Simply enter “0” (zero) on the first line of the Institution.</p>  
      <p>Transcribe an Institution in the sequence that the people are recorded in the census pages. This means that it is not always possible to maintain the usual family groupings where, for example, a Lighthouse Station has the staff listed first and then the various wives and children.</p>

      <h4>Field F: House Number</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter up to 4 numerals plus an optional suffix, <strong>####a</strong>, or the column may be left blank.</li>
      </ul> 
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>House numbers may be found in the column on the census page which is associated with the street name. Enter the house number in column F on the first line of the household, but leave blank where no house number is given. House numbers were not generally recorded in the <strong>1841</strong> census.</p>
      <p>Where house numbers are compounded (as in “23 &amp; 24”, “1–4”, “2½” or “2 Back”), enter only the first number (or the integer part) in this field, and then type the full address in column G.  For example, if the address is recorded as “114 &amp; 116 High Street”, then put the House Number in column F as “114” and put the Address in column G as “114 &amp; 116 High St”.&#160; &#160;or if “2½ Colliery Row”&#160; “2”&#160; would be entered in this column and “2.5 Colliery Row” in column G.</p>

      <h4>Field G: Street or Road Address</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and can be up to 30 characters</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Copy the address as recorded — even if it looks wrong! The address should be entered only once, on the first line of the household, even where the household is split over two pages. Where the address is given only at the top of the second page, then move the address to the beginning of the household.</p>
      <p>If no address is recorded, then enter “-” (a hyphen). Do not assume that the address is necessarily the same as for the previous household, unless a repeater word or mark (such as “ditto” or “do”) has clearly been recorded.</p>
      <p>Transcribe any supplementary information after the street name, as in “High&#160;Street, Anchor Hotel”.  Where necessary for reasons of lack of space, you may use abbreviations such as “St”, “Rd”, “Terr”, etc. Enter any additional information that will not fit here into <a href="#notes">column Y</a>.</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Shipping Returns:</h5>
      <p>Enter the address for a Shipping Return as the vessel name in brackets (parentheses) followed by the home port, the port of origin, if given, e.g. “(Prince Consort) Aberdeen”.</p>
      <p>If space is short, you may omit the “HMS” part of a Royal Navy vessel name: the use of “0#2” in column B will indicate that it is a Royal Navy vessel.</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Scotland:</h5>
      <p>In <strong>1841</strong>, if an address is written at the top of the page, and only at the top, then it can be used for the other households on that page.</p>
      <p>From <strong>1851 onwards</strong>, an address can be copied for other households in the same building, but not between buildings unless the enumerator has used a repeater word or mark (such as “ditto”). If the next building has no address given, enter “-” (a hyphen).</p>

      <h4 id="H">Field H: Query or Special Use</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>x</strong>, <strong>u</strong>, <strong>b</strong>, <strong>n</strong>, or <strong>v</strong>), or leave the column blank. Any other entry will be rejected in the FreeCEN process as invalid.</li>
      </ul> 
      <h5>Guidance:</h5> 
      <p>The most frequently used character is <strong>x</strong> and this should be entered in column H where you have doubts about the interpretation of any of the columns E, F or G. Write a brief comment in <a href="#notes">column Y</a> to explain the nature of your doubts, e.g. “?house number”.</p>
      <p>Alternatively, one of the characters <strong>b</strong>, <strong>u</strong>, <strong>n</strong>, or <strong>v</strong> may be entered in column H.  If any one of these characters is entered in column H, then any information entered in columns I to X (but not in column Y) will be ignored.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter <strong>b</strong> if the enumerator has recorded a house being built</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>u</strong> if the enumerator has recorded an uninhabited house</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>v</strong> if the enumerator indicates that the family are away or visiting</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>n</strong> to show that a Schedule Number is missing, one line for each unused number.  This proves the omission to be in the census return, and not made at the transcription!</li> 
        <li>Also enter <strong>n</strong> in the case of deleted addresses, as for example where a note on the census page states that “Three schedules numbered for the Light House not required, being provided with a schedule from the Trinity Board”. In this instance, type the address as “Light House”, put <strong>n</strong> in column H and the note in column Y.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Please note that where an enumerator has grouped vacant premises as a single entry (such as “4b” or “2u”), each of the premises must be treated as a separate household with its own schedule number, even though this may be zero.  Sometimes the enumerator started the next household on the same line as vacant premises. You should always enter them on separate rows.</p>
      <p>Similarly, vacant premises cannot occur within a household, for instance where the enumerator may have added “1u”, having previously forgotten it.  Normally, you should enter the vacancy immediately after the household with residents.</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Shipping:</h5>
      <p>Occasionally you may find a (foreign) ship that is named but with no crew details. Enter <strong>v</strong> in column H and put any extra information in the Notes field: for example, the (Louise Frederick) came from Norway, had five crew on board who were not named, nor were any personal details provided — you enter “(Louise Frederick) Norway” in column G, “v” in H, and “five crew, unnamed” in Y.</p>
    </div>
