    <div id="person">
      <h3>Personal Details</h3>

      <h4>Field I: Surname</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and can be up to 24 characters</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>

      <h5 class="guide">Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Copy the Surname as it appears on the census page — even if it looks wrong, or is known to be wrong!  Any repeater word or mark (such as “ditto” or “do”) must be expanded in full.</p>
      <p>You <em>must</em> enter something in column I for every person in a household. If a surname is not given, enter “-” (a hyphen). If the enumerator has put “unknown” or something similar, transcribe as “(Unknown)”.</p>
      <p>Please note that the Surname is the field which researchers will generally be searching on, so you should always use your best endeavours to interpret correctly what is written on the census page.  If it is unclear (because it is poorly written, smudged or covered by marks) or where it is uncertain (because the individual letters are difficult to interpret), then raise a query in <a href="#K">column K</a> to bring it to the attention of the Proofreader and put an explanatory note in <a href="#notes">column Y</a>.</p>

      <h5>Guidance for Scotland:</h5>
      <p>Sometimes, the Scottish census will record two surnames for a wife.  Enter both of the names, separated by a space, followed by a /, followed by a space, as in “murray&#160;/&#160;smith”. Where it is clear, enter the married surname first.</p>

      <h4>Field J: Forename(s)</h4>

      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and can be up to 24 characters</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>

      <h5 class="guide">Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Copy forenames as they appear on the census page — even if they look wrong, or are known to be wrong!  Type abbreviated names as recorded: do not, for example, expand “Thos” to “Thomas” or “Margt” to “Margaret”. Do not put a “.” after an abbreviated forename.</p>
      <p>Allow one space between any names, initials, or words.  Where necessary for reasons of lack of space, you may reduce later forenames to an initial, but always spell the first name as recorded. Add a note of any abbreviations you make in <a href="#notes">column Y</a>.</p>
      <p>You <em>must</em> enter something in column J for everyone in a household. Where no forename has been recorded, you should enter “-” (a hyphen) in column J.</p>
      <p>Type any titles after forenames and enclose in brackets (parentheses): for example, “Mary (Mrs)”, “Charles (Rev)”, “Wm (Dr)”, “John (Prof)”, “Elizabeth (Lady Chalfont)”, etc.</p>
      <h5>Guidance for Scotland</h5>
      <p>If the enumerator has put “unbaptised”, or “infant”, or not recorded a name for an child under one year, put “(Unnamed)”.</p>

      <h4 id="K">Field K: Query</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>x</strong>), or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter an <strong>x</strong> if you have doubts about the interpretation of the names in either field I or field J. Write a brief comment in <a href="#notes">field Y</a> to explain the nature of your doubt, for example, “?forename”.</p>

      <h4>Field L: Relationship to Head</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter up to 6 characters</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>

      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter the relationship recorded on the census page if it is no longer than six characters.  If it is longer, then refer to the table of standard abbreviations in <a href="/information-for-transcribers/abbreviations#relations">Appendix 2</a>. If there isn't a standard form of abbreviation in the table, then use similar principles described in our <a href="/information-for-transcribers/abbreviations#abbrev">Abbreviations policy</a> to create one, and note the relationship in full in <a href="#notes">column Y</a>.</p>
      <p>If no relationship is shown on the census page, enter “-” (a hyphen).  Please note that the <strong>1841</strong> Census did not record this information, and column L can be left blank.</p>

      <h4>Field M: (Marital) Status</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>The entry can be one character (<strong>m</strong>, <strong>s</strong>, <strong>u</strong> or <strong>w</strong>)</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter the marital status recorded on the census page as follows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter <strong>m</strong> where the status is indicated as married</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>s</strong> where the status is indicated as single (1891 only)</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>u</strong> where the status is indicated as unmarried (1851, 1861 and 1871)</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>w</strong> where the status is indicated as widowed</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If no status is recorded, enter “-” (a hyphen). The <strong>1841</strong> census did not record this information, and column M can be left blank.</p>

      <h4>Field N: Gender Male/Female</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and is a single character (<strong>m</strong> or <strong>f</strong>)</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The enumerator was required to enter the age of a person in one of two columns on the census page, headed Male and Female.  FreeCEN transcribes this as a single letter, <strong>m</strong> or <strong>f</strong>.  Where the age is missing, you should normally enter a hyphen.</p>
      <p>You should generally transcribe the gender according to the column in which the enumerator has entered the age, even where this appears to be wrong.  You can leave a note of explanation in <a href="#notes">column Y</a>. However, where the relationship to the head of household makes the gender clear (for instance, son or daughter), then you should enter the gender that matches that relationship.</p>

      <h4>Field O: Age</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry here is <strong>required</strong> and can be up to 3 numerals plus a single character (<strong>y</strong>, <strong>m</strong>, <strong>w</strong> or <strong>d</strong>), <strong>###a</strong> </li>
        <li>Do not put a space between the number and the letter</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter the age as shown on the census page, applying the following rules:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Where the age is shown in years, enter the number of years. There is no need to enter <strong>y</strong> for years, as this will be automatically assumed in the FreeCEN process.  Any number between 1 and 120 will be accepted.  Ignore any fractions of years over 2 years, and add the further detail in column Y.  Any fractions of less than 2 years should be converted to months. For any age in years that includes a fraction, put the whole number in field O, and the full entry in field Y: for example, for a stated age of 7½, put “7” in field O and “Age 7.5” in field Y.</li>
        <li>Where the age is shown in months, enter the number followed by <strong>m</strong>. Any number between 1 and 24 will be accepted.  Where the age in months exceeds 24, round the figure down to years, and add the further detail in column Y.</li>
        <li>Where the age is shown in weeks, enter the number followed by <strong>w</strong>. Any number between 1 and 20 will be accepted.</li>
        <li>Where the age is shown in days, enter the number followed by <strong>d</strong>. Any number between 1 and 30 will be accepted.</li>
        <li>If the age is shown as “less than 1 month”, enter as “1m”.</li>
        <li>If no age is shown, or the figure is unreadable, enter <strong>999</strong>. It is not acceptable to enter “0” (zero) or “-” (a hyphen).</li>
        <li>Note that ages of less than 14 years for males and less than 12 years for females are not acceptable where the marital status is entered as <strong>m</strong> (married) or <strong>w</strong> (widowed).  If these limits are breached, you will need to enter the age as given, flag, and leave a note in column Y.</li>
        <li>Note also that ages of less than 2 years or more than 17 years are not acceptable where the occupation of the person is entered as scholar.  Outside these limits, you will need to enter the transcription of the occupation as “student (orig: scholar)”.</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Field P: Query</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>The entry may be a single character (<strong>x</strong>), or the column may be left blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter an <strong>x</strong> in column P where you have doubts about the interpretation of any of the columns L, M, N or O. Write a brief comment in <a href="#notes">column Y</a> to explain the nature of your doubts, e.g. “?age”.</p>
    </div>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <div id="job">
      <h3>Rank, Profession or Occupation</h3>

      <div class="push--bottom"> Return to <a href="#index">On this page</a> </div>

      <h4>Field Q: Occupation</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry can be up to 30 characters (but only 24 in 1891), or it can be left blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The general approach to transcribing occupations should be to copy what appears on the census page.  However, census enumerators were given permission to abbreviate a number of common occupations, and it is FreeCEN policy to expand these to assist the researcher where we can be sure of the meaning intended. The list is in <a href="/information-for-transcribers/abbreviations#occupation" title="Abbreviations">Appendix 4</a>.  Also, where the enumerator has used a repeater word or mark (such as “ditto” or “do”), the occupation must be expanded in full.
</p>
      <p>Some descriptions of occupations can be lengthy, and it may then be necessary to abbreviate certain words to keep within the 30 characters allowed.  Always try to ensure that such abbreviations are unambiguous, using the principles demonstrated in <a href="/information-for-transcribers/abbreviations#abbrev">Appendix 1</a>, and if necessary leave a note of explanation in <a href="#notes">column Y</a>. Alternatively, simply split the entry between this field and the Notes field.</p>
      <p>The <strong>1891 Census</strong> introduced additional columns to indicate whether a person was an employer, employee or neither.  This information is transcribed separately in column R (see below) but, as a consequence, the number of available characters to transcribe the occupation in column Q is reduced from 30 to 24.  This may mean that the occupation has to be more frequently abbreviated, but please still ensure that such abbreviations are unambiguous and, if necessary, supported by a note of explanation in column Y.</p>
    
      <h4>Field R: Employment Category</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>e</strong>,<strong> r </strong>or<strong> n</strong>), or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>

      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The employment category only appears in the <strong>1891</strong> Census.  Otherwise column R may be left blank.</p>
      <p>The enumerators were asked to put a cross in one of three columns to indicate the employment status of a person.  This information should be transcribed as follows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter <strong>r</strong> when the enumerator placed a cross in the column headed Employer</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>e</strong> when the enumerator placed a cross in the column headed Employed</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>n</strong> when the enumerator placed a cross in the column headed Neither Employer nor Employed</li>
        <li>If a person is identified as both Employer and Employee, then enter <strong>r</strong>
</li>
        <li>Leave column R blank if all three columns are empty</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Field S: Query</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>x</strong>), or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter an <strong>x</strong> in column S where you have doubts about the interpretation of either of the columns Q or R. Write a brief comment in <a href="#notes">Column Y</a> to explain the nature of your doubts, e.g. “?occupation”.</p>
    
    </div> 
    <div class="landmark text--right">Return to <a href="#pageNav">On this page</a> </div>
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <div id="birthplace">
      <h3>Birthplace &amp; Sundries</h3>

      <h4>Field T: Where Born County</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and takes the form of a three-letter Chapman Code</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>The entry in column T must be taken from the list of Chapman Codes in <a href="/information-for-transcribers/abbreviations#chapman">Appendix 3</a>.  Enter the county (or country) as it appears on the census page, even where it may appear to be wrong.  Where no county is recorded, you should only enter one if the <em>Place</em> of birth leaves no doubts. Remember that many British place names appear in more than one county.</p>
      <p>Where the place of birth is outside the British Isles:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter “OVB” if the person is stated to be a British subject <em>or</em> was born in a country which formed part of the British Empire at the time [insert link]</li>
        <li>Enter “OVF” if the person is not stated to be a British subject <em>and</em> was born in any other foreign country</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="islet islet--bordered"><p>The <strong>British Isles</strong> of the 19<sup>th</sup> Century consisted of England, Ireland, Scotland, Wales, the Isle of Man and the Channel Isles: naturally, none of these places counts as overseas for any of the censuses we are transcribing.</p> </div>

      <p>Where no county or country is shown, or where there is any doubt about what should be entered, then enter “UNK”.  If necessary, please add a note of explanation in column Y.</p>
      <p>Special rules apply for the <strong>1841</strong> Census, where the questions asked were whether the person was born in the same county, and if not whether the person was born in another country of the British Isles or in Foreign Parts.  The rules to be applied for the 1841 Census are as follows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>If born in the same county, enter the Chapman Code for that County</li>
        <li>If born out of the county, enter “OUC”</li>
        <li>If born in another country of the British Isles, enter the Chapman Code for that country</li>
        <li>If born in Foreign Parts, enter “OVF”</li>
        <li>If the enumerator recorded another specific county, then enter that Chapman Code</li>
        <li>If there was no indication of place of birth or it is unclear what should be entered, then enter “UNK”</li>
      </ul>
    
      <h4>Field U: Where born Place</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column is <strong>required</strong> and can be up to 20 characters</li>
        <li>The default entry is “-” (a hyphen)</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter the place of birth as it is written on the census page.  Do not attempt to correct or modernise the spelling of place names. If you believe the spelling should be corrected, then enter an x in column V and leave a note in column Y.  If you have difficulty reading or interpreting the writing, then you can use the <a class="go" href="http://www.gazetteer.org.uk" title="http://www.gazetteer.org.uk">Gazetteer of British Place Names</a>, the <a class="go" href="https://www.genuki.org.uk/gazetteer" title="https://www.genuki.org.uk/gazetteer">GenUKI gazetteer</a> or search on <a class="go" href="http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/" title="http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/">Vision of Britain</a>. For place names in Wales, the <a class="go" href="https://historicplacenames.rcahmw.gov.uk/" title="https://historicplacenames.rcahmw.gov.uk/">RCAHMW historic place names site </a> and for places in Scotland, <a class="go" href="https://scotlandsplaces.gov.uk/search/alphabet" title="https://scotlandsplaces.gov.uk/search/alphabet">Scotland's Places</a> could be helpful. We also have a <a href="<%= asset_path('7g0q70etya_CHAPMAN_CODES_AND_POB.pdf') %>" title="Chapman Codes And PoB">pdf of place names</a>, which you can <a href="<%= asset_path('d9nhe59xc_Using_CHAPMAN_CODES_Genie_FIND_facility_in_the_PDF.pdf') %>" title="Using Chapman Codes (Genie) Find Facility in the PDF">search using these instructions</a>.</p>
      <p>If no place of birth is indicated (other than possibly a county or country, for which you enter the Chapman Code in column T), then enter “-” (a hyphen).  The <strong>1841</strong> Census did not record the place of birth, and column U can be left blank.</p>
      <p>Avoid abbreviating wherever possible.  Where the length of the birthplace makes this unavoidable, rearrange the birthplace to make sure that the essential information can be written in full with the principal town at the start of the line.  For instance, a birthplace recorded as “Notre Dame, Paris, France” (25 characters) should be entered as “OVF” in column T and as “Paris, Notre Dame” (17 characters) in column U.</p>
    
      <h4>Field V: Query</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>x</strong>), or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter an <strong>x</strong> in column V where you have doubts about the interpretation of either of the columns T or U. Write a brief comment in <a href="#notes">column Y</a> to explain the nature of your doubts, e.g. “?birthplace”.</p>
    
      <h4>Field W: Disability</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter up to 6 characters, or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>Enter the information shown on the census page if it is no longer than six characters. If it is longer, then abbreviate as necessary and enter the full wording in <a href="#notes">column Y</a>.</p>
      <p>This information was not recorded in the <strong>1841</strong> Census, and column W can be left blank.</p>
    
      <h4>Field X: Welsh Spoken</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter a single character (<strong>w</strong>, <strong>e</strong> or <strong>b</strong>), or leave the column blank</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>This information was only collected in the <strong>1891</strong> Census in Welsh Counties. Otherwise, column X may be left blank. Where appropriate, enter the information on the census page as follows:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Enter <strong>w</strong> if only Welsh spoken</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>e</strong> if only English spoken</li>
        <li>Enter <strong>b</strong> if both Welsh and English spoken</li>
        <li>Leave column X blank if the information was not recorded</li>
      </ul>
    
    </div> 
    <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />

    <div id="notes">
      <h3>Notes &amp; <q>Mynotes</q> </h3>
      <div class="push--bottom">Return to <a href="#pageNav">On this page</a> </div>

      <h4>Field Y: Notes</h4>
      <h5>Requirements:</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>An entry in this column can be up to 44 characters</li>
      </ul>
      <h5>Guidance:</h5>
      <p>This column is used to enter additional information which cannot be accommodated in the space available in the previous columns.  You can also use it to record the number of rooms with windows, where stated: for example, “3 rooms”. The other use of this column is for expanding on any queries you have about the entries on the census page.</p>
      <p>Any entry in this column that may become part of the database, such as a suggested alternative spelling for an address or place of birth, should include upper-case letters where appropriate.</p>
      <p>Column Y is intended for brief information or explanation of queries.  Where further explanation is required or where you need to explain several queries about a single entry, then do this in a separate file — see the next section for details.</p>
    
      <h4>mynotes.txt</h4>
      <p>Please note that this is not the only way to send additional notes about your transcription — be guided by your Coordinator.</p>
      <p>You will find it useful to make a plain text file named <strong>mynotes.txt</strong> (using NotePad on Windows, or TextEdit on a Mac) into which you can write any extended comments that could help the Proofreader. Have the file open when you transcribe so that it is always ready to use. Rename the file with the Piece Number, so your Proofreader and Validator can easily identify it among the very many mynotes.txt files that they will get.</p>
      <p>Please identify the record you are explaining by quoting the ED, Folio and Schedule numbers as well as the person's name. Unfortunately, while it would be easier to quote the row number from your spreadsheet, this will have no meaning once your file has been processed, ready for Proofreading.&#160;</p>
      <p>Send your mynotes.txt file to your Coordinator with your completed spreadsheet.</p>
    </div> 

  </div>
</div>
